	     <form action=/cgi-bin/mrate.pl name=f109189363862578>
	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=/db/item.html?item=5628&mid=109189363862578>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=/db/item.html?item=5628&mid=109189363862578>Any good?</a> <a id=fs8 href=/db/item.html?item=5628&mid=109189363862578#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Sat, Aug 7th 11:47 AM 2004</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=115474><span id= >Summerain</span></a><br><span id=notbold>9 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [3.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>I am not certain what the formulas are.&nbsp;&nbsp;I have used the reaver for my low level twinks for about 2 years.  What I found was this:<br>With a Wide Bladed Greatsword my toons had fewer hit points remaining when the mob died than with the Reaver.  The same result with other 2 hs.  The result vs dual wield varied.  I used a Wurmy and Centi LS, a Defiance and Lamentation,  etc.  With some I had more hps left when the mob was dead, with others fewer hps.  I did not do any of this scientifically, obviously.  My beliefs are based on completely empirical (observed) data.  The Reaver is great weapon.  <br>I particularly like the resist stats, but I have several high end characters that resist stats are important to.  I will mention that they use other weapons with even better damage/delay ratios.  :=).  <br></p>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
